<h4>MORE HEALTH NEWS</h4>

<ul><li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/06/house-bill-1003-colorado-naloxone-opioid-reversal-schools/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>How a friend&#8217;s death turned Colorado teens into anti-overdose activists.</strong></a><strong> </strong>When a 15-year-old died in Durango in 2021 from an accidental fentanyl poisoning, the memorial service was so packed people had to stand outside the funeral home. Now, his friends are hoping to change state law to prevent such tragedies from happening again. The teens are advocating for <a target="_blank"  href="https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/hb24-1003">House Bill 1003</a>, which would ensure that students can carry naloxone with them at all times without fear of discipline or confiscation. As <strong>Rae Ellen Bichell</strong> reports, the bill could make Colorado the first state with a law explicitly protecting possession of naloxone at school.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” KFF Health News</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/02/colorado-construction-workers-suicide/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Colorado construction workers, pressured by longer, harder hours, die by suicide twice as often as other professions.</strong></a><strong> </strong>Colorado has the sixth-highest rate of deaths by suicide, but the suicide rate for people who work in construction is even higher. Among all people who died by suicide in Colorado in 2021, 13% worked in the construction industry, a larger proportion than any other profession, including people who are unemployed or nonworking. Economic instability, the stress of a potentially hazardous workplace, alcohol use and a disproportionately male workforce all contribute to the high rates. But, as <strong>Jenny McCoy</strong> reports, some are working to bring better mental health to the construction industry.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Trust</strong></li>

<li><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/03/01/colorado-medical-aid-in-dying-bill-pared-back/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>Colorado&#8217;s medical aid-in-dying residency requirement won&#8217;t be lifted.</strong></a><strong> </strong>Lawmakers this year had considered a bill <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2024/01/30/colorado-aid-in-dying-law-changes/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=*|MC:SUBJECT|*_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email">that would have removed requirements</a> limiting Colorado&#8217;s medical aid-in-dying law to only Colorado residents. But, as <strong>Jesse Paul</strong> reports, the bill has been stripped back and the residency requirement will remain. But the bill does still lower the waiting period to seven days, from 15.<strong><br></strong><strong>â€” The Colorado Sun</strong></li>
</ul>

